{"response":{"status":"ok","userTier":"internal","total":1,"content":{"id":"environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"liveblog","sectionId":"environment","webTitle":"Is Obama's climate plan enough to 'stop the planet being beyond fixing'?","blocks":{"body":[{"lastModifiedDate":"2013-06-26T15:32:26Z","lastModifiedBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"published":true,"title":"My verdict","createdDate":"2013-06-26T15:15:27Z","createdBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"elements":[{"assets":[],"textTypeData":{"html":"<p>Obama, as ever, scored highly on inspiring rhetoric. For some, this was the most important aspect of his speech, given how little to date his presidency has offered the so-called &quot;climate concerned&quot;. He gave the strong impression that climate change was back, square and centre, on the Oval Office desk, something he had promised on the election trail, both in 2008 and 2012.</p> \n<p>But details matter when it comes to climate and energy policies. And details were lacking in his speech. We still don&apos;t know, for example, what he intends to do with the Keystone pipeline. What does he mean by &quot;significantly&quot; when he says he will authorise it, but only if it &quot;does not significantly exacerbate the climate problem&quot;? And without instruments such as carbon taxes and &quot;cap and trade&quot;, how can we be sure that his beloved shale gas only ever replaces coal and not, as some fear, also curtails growth in renewables?</p> \n<p>And what of the wider question of whether the US&apos;s current emissions targets are enough to help prevent global temperatures rising above 2C over the course of this century? Judging by the calculations of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">Prof Piers Forster</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cafaa9e4b0e2a9937599df\">Dr Chris Hope</a>, it would appear the current targets are woefully short of where they need to be. But, if we&apos;re being honest, we already knew that.</p> \n<p>Therefore, Obama&apos;s speech can certainly be spun positively as &quot;better late than never&quot;, but a pragmatic assessment must conclude that the US is still making baby steps when huge strides forward are required. This is not the global leadership so many wish the US to take on climate change.</p>"},"type":"text"}],"bodyTextSummary":"Obama, as ever, scored highly on inspiring rhetoric. For some, this was the most important aspect of his speech, given how little to date his presidency has offered the so-called \"climate concerned\". He gave the strong impression that climate change was back, square and centre, on the Oval Office desk, something he had promised on the election trail, both in 2008 and 2012. But details matter when it comes to climate and energy policies. And details were lacking in his speech. We still don't know, for example, what he intends to do with the Keystone pipeline. What does he mean by \"significantly\" when he says he will authorise it, but only if it \"does not significantly exacerbate the climate problem\"? And without instruments such as carbon taxes and \"cap and trade\", how can we be sure that his beloved shale gas only ever replaces coal and not, as some fear, also curtails growth in renewables? And what of the wider question of whether the US's current emissions targets are enough to help prevent global temperatures rising above 2C over the course of this century? Judging by the calculations of Prof Piers Forster and Dr Chris Hope, it would appear the current targets are woefully short of where they need to be. But, if we're being honest, we already knew that. Therefore, Obama's speech can certainly be spun positively as \"better late than never\", but a pragmatic assessment must conclude that the US is still making baby steps when huge strides forward are required. This is not the global leadership so many wish the US to take on climate change.","bodyHtml":"<p>Obama, as ever, scored highly on inspiring rhetoric. For some, this was the most important aspect of his speech, given how little to date his presidency has offered the so-called &quot;climate concerned&quot;. He gave the strong impression that climate change was back, square and centre, on the Oval Office desk, something he had promised on the election trail, both in 2008 and 2012.</p> <p>But details matter when it comes to climate and energy policies. And details were lacking in his speech. We still don&apos;t know, for example, what he intends to do with the Keystone pipeline. What does he mean by &quot;significantly&quot; when he says he will authorise it, but only if it &quot;does not significantly exacerbate the climate problem&quot;? And without instruments such as carbon taxes and &quot;cap and trade&quot;, how can we be sure that his beloved shale gas only ever replaces coal and not, as some fear, also curtails growth in renewables?</p> <p>And what of the wider question of whether the US&apos;s current emissions targets are enough to help prevent global temperatures rising above 2C over the course of this century? Judging by the calculations of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">Prof Piers Forster</a> and <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cafaa9e4b0e2a9937599df\">Dr Chris Hope</a>, it would appear the current targets are woefully short of where they need to be. But, if we&apos;re being honest, we already knew that.</p> <p>Therefore, Obama&apos;s speech can certainly be spun positively as &quot;better late than never&quot;, but a pragmatic assessment must conclude that the US is still making baby steps when huge strides forward are required. This is not the global leadership so many wish the US to take on climate change.</p>","attributes":{"keyEvent":"true","title":"My verdict"},"id":"51cb058fe4b0a53e53280c8d","firstPublishedDate":"2013-06-26T15:32:27Z","publishedDate":"2013-06-26T15:32:27Z","contributors":[]},{"lastModifiedDate":"2013-06-26T14:28:57Z","lastModifiedBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"published":true,"createdDate":"2013-06-26T14:28:57Z","createdBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"elements":[{"assets":[],"textTypeData":{"html":"<p>Reacting to the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">earlier analysis</a> by Prof Piers Forster, <a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/research/faculty/hopec.html\">Dr Chris Hope</a>, a climate change policy researcher and PAGE model developer at the <a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/\">University of Cambridge Judge Business School</a>, has sent me his <a href=\"http://www.chrishopepolicy.com/2013/06/how-much-will-the-world-benefit-from-obamas-climate-plan/\">own calculations</a>:</p> \n<blockquote> \n <p>Piers Forster made <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">some initial calculations</a> that a 17% drop in US emissions by 2020 could reduce CO2 concentrations in 2100 by between 3 and 5 ppm, and reduce temperature rises by between 0.02C and 0.04C compared to where they would be without the US plan. But Piers’s calculation used just a single value for equilibrium climate sensitivity (ECS) of 3C.</p> \n <p>The PAGE09 model (<a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/research/working_papers/2011/wp1104.pdf\">pdf</a>) uses a range of climate sensitivities consistent with the latest IPCC reports. Running Obama’s plan to reduce US emissions by 17% by 2020 through 10,000 runs of the PAGE09 model confirms that, with a range of ECS values, the plan will reduce global mean temperatures by between 0.012C and 0.032C by 2100 (5-95% values), with a most likely reduction of 0.02C, compared to business as usual. The PAGE09 model can also do what Piers could not, and make an estimate of how much this drop in temperatures would reduce global damages from climate change. The answer is it will reduce them by between 0.5 and 10.5 trillion dollars (5-95% values), with a mean reduction in damage of 4.5 trillion dollars.</p> \n <p>As <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/25/obama-climate-speech-expert-verdict\">other commentators have said</a>, it’s a start.</p> \n <p>(Details: US CO2 emissions assumed to be 17% below base year (2008) emissions from 2020 until 2075. Comparison with IPCC A1B business as usual scenario.)</p> \n</blockquote>"},"type":"text"}],"bodyTextSummary":"Reacting to the earlier analysis by Prof Piers Forster, Dr Chris Hope, a climate change policy researcher and PAGE model developer at the University of Cambridge Judge Business School, has sent me his own calculations: Piers Forster made some initial calculations that a 17% drop in US emissions by 2020 could reduce CO2 concentrations in 2100 by between 3 and 5 ppm, and reduce temperature rises by between 0.02C and 0.04C compared to where they would be without the US plan. But Piers’s calculation used just a single value for equilibrium climate sensitivity (ECS) of 3C. The PAGE09 model (pdf) uses a range of climate sensitivities consistent with the latest IPCC reports. Running Obama’s plan to reduce US emissions by 17% by 2020 through 10,000 runs of the PAGE09 model confirms that, with a range of ECS values, the plan will reduce global mean temperatures by between 0.012C and 0.032C by 2100 (5-95% values), with a most likely reduction of 0.02C, compared to business as usual. The PAGE09 model can also do what Piers could not, and make an estimate of how much this drop in temperatures would reduce global damages from climate change. The answer is it will reduce them by between 0.5 and 10.5 trillion dollars (5-95% values), with a mean reduction in damage of 4.5 trillion dollars. As other commentators have said, it’s a start. (Details: US CO2 emissions assumed to be 17% below base year (2008) emissions from 2020 until 2075. Comparison with IPCC A1B business as usual scenario.)","bodyHtml":"<p>Reacting to the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">earlier analysis</a> by Prof Piers Forster, <a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/research/faculty/hopec.html\">Dr Chris Hope</a>, a climate change policy researcher and PAGE model developer at the <a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/\">University of Cambridge Judge Business School</a>, has sent me his <a href=\"http://www.chrishopepolicy.com/2013/06/how-much-will-the-world-benefit-from-obamas-climate-plan/\">own calculations</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>Piers Forster made <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/26/barack-obama-climate-action-plan#block-51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11\">some initial calculations</a> that a 17% drop in US emissions by 2020 could reduce CO2 concentrations in 2100 by between 3 and 5 ppm, and reduce temperature rises by between 0.02C and 0.04C compared to where they would be without the US plan. But Piers’s calculation used just a single value for equilibrium climate sensitivity (ECS) of 3C.</p> <p>The PAGE09 model (<a href=\"http://www.jbs.cam.ac.uk/research/working_papers/2011/wp1104.pdf\">pdf</a>) uses a range of climate sensitivities consistent with the latest IPCC reports. Running Obama’s plan to reduce US emissions by 17% by 2020 through 10,000 runs of the PAGE09 model confirms that, with a range of ECS values, the plan will reduce global mean temperatures by between 0.012C and 0.032C by 2100 (5-95% values), with a most likely reduction of 0.02C, compared to business as usual. The PAGE09 model can also do what Piers could not, and make an estimate of how much this drop in temperatures would reduce global damages from climate change. The answer is it will reduce them by between 0.5 and 10.5 trillion dollars (5-95% values), with a mean reduction in damage of 4.5 trillion dollars.</p> <p>As <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/blog/2013/jun/25/obama-climate-speech-expert-verdict\">other commentators have said</a>, it’s a start.</p> <p>(Details: US CO2 emissions assumed to be 17% below base year (2008) emissions from 2020 until 2075. Comparison with IPCC A1B business as usual scenario.)</p> </blockquote>","attributes":{},"id":"51cafaa9e4b0e2a9937599df","firstPublishedDate":"2013-06-26T14:28:57Z","publishedDate":"2013-06-26T14:28:57Z","contributors":[]},{"lastModifiedDate":"2013-06-26T12:50:54Z","lastModifiedBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"published":true,"createdDate":"2013-06-26T12:50:54Z","createdBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"elements":[{"assets":[],"textTypeData":{"html":"<p><a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/25/obama-tries-the-kitchen-sink-approach-to-global-warming/?e\">Brad Plumer&apos;s analysis</a> on the Washington Post&apos;s Wonkblog is worth a read:</p> \n<blockquote> \n <p>If you take a look around the world, averting climate change looks like a daunting task. Global emissions <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/carbon-dioxide-emissions-rose-14-percent-in-2012-iea-report-says/2013/06/09/35d32bac-d123-11e2-8cbe-1bcbee06f8f8_story.html\">soared to record levels</a> last year. The World Bank <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2012/11/19/were-on-pace-for-4c-of-global-warming-heres-why-the-world-bank-is-terrified/\">is warning</a> that the Earth is on pace to heat up more than 2°C by century’s end, and possibly as much as 4°C (7.2°F) if the worst-case scenarios pan out — a level, it says, that humanity might be unable to adapt to. And international climate talks are barely limping along.</p> \n <p>For now, then, the minimum that the United States can do is try to meet the near-term climate goals that Obama promised as part of the Copenhagen Accord a few years back. That would require reducing U.S. emissions 17 percent below 2005 levels by 2020. Right now, the country isn’t on pace to do that:</p> \n</blockquote>"},"type":"text"},{"assets":[{"file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/26/1372250960669/60b84812-ce1c-4f3e-a0a0-047373584986-380x228.png","mimeType":"image/png","type":"image","typeData":{"width":380,"name":"380x228","height":228}},{"file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/26/1372250961103/8fa33059-36f6-46e4-9aa9-0381965db7e8-300x180.png","mimeType":"image/png","type":"image","typeData":{"width":300,"name":"300x180","height":180}},{"file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/26/1372250961322/00deca7e-5a40-4347-8378-9e18751fca0d-140x84.png","mimeType":"image/png","type":"image","typeData":{"width":140,"name":"140x84","height":84}},{"file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/26/1372250961619/5a0b7505-57f9-4b08-b847-4b8a9199ddaf-bestSizeAvailable.png","mimeType":"image/png","type":"image","typeData":{"width":585,"name":"bestSizeAvailable","height":351}},{"file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/26/1372250961906/32d00e9c-1ad2-40a1-a036-7226d931b943-220x132.png","mimeType":"image/png","type":"image","typeData":{"width":220,"name":"220x132","height":132}},{"file":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/6/26/1372250962466/d79ba6a6-60e0-45b2-ad90-a681473ce5e2-460x276.png","mimeType":"image/png","type":"image","typeData":{"width":460,"name":"460x276"