nomic downturn and a 10% reduction in US emissions since 2005 (1), global emissions are roughly following the worst-case emission scenarios that will be used in the upcoming Intergovernmental Panel for Climate Change Report (2).</p> \n <p>Commentators are at odds about exactly what cuts the new policy will achieve, but if we optimistically assume that US emissions will follow the Copenhagen agreement and reduce by 17% from 2005-2020 (3), this could save up to 1000 million metric tonnes of global CO2 emissions (around 3% of current world values). If we further assume that this is a real global cut from the worse-case scenario and emissions growth elsewhere doesn’t compensate (as previously happened with huge growth in China over 2005-2011), we can go on to calculate the effect on atmospheric CO2 levels and temperature.</p> \n <p>To do this we estimated CO2 changes with the Bern pulse carbon cycle model (4) and temperature changes by using a simple model of climate (5) that is tuned to the latest climate model projections from our recent paper (6). These cuts acting alone would have a small but significant effect, reducing projected CO2 levels by 3 ppm in 2050 and 5 ppm in 2100, giving us between 0.02 and 0.04 C less warming in 2050 and staving off passing the 2C warming mark by 2-5 years. This may seem small as current levels of 400 ppm could easily pass 500 ppm by 2050, but every little helps.</p> \n <ol> \n  <li>US emissions were 5940 million metric tonnes in 2005 and 5420 million metric tonnes in 2011. EDGAR database. <a href=\"http://edgar.jrc.ec.europa.eu/overview.php?v=CO2ts1990-2011&amp;sort=des9\">http://edgar.jrc.ec.europa.eu/overview.php?v=CO2ts1990-2011&amp;sort=des9</a> </li> \n  <li>Scenario used is a “Representative Concentration Pathways&quot; (RCP) RCP8.5, see <a href=\"http://www.pik-potsdam.de/~mmalte/rcps/\">http://www.pik-potsdam.de/~mmalte/rcps/</a></li> \n  <li><a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/23/obama-is-announcing-new-climate-actions-tuesday-this-chart-explains-why/\">http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/23/obama-is-announcing-new-climate-actions-tuesday-this-chart-explains-why/</a></li> \n  <li><a href=\"http://unfccc.int/resource/brazil/carbon.html\">http://unfccc.int/resource/brazil/carbon.html</a></li> \n  <li><a href=\"http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v6/n6/full/ngeo1836.html\">http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v6/n6/full/ngeo1836.html</a></li> \n  <li><a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jgrd.50174/abstract\">http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jgrd.50174/abstract</a></li> \n </ol> \n</blockquote>"},"type":"text"}],"bodyTextSummary":"Earlier, I noticed this tweet by Prof Piers Forster, a climate scientist based at the University of Leeds...\nSo I emailed him to ask if he could send me his more detailed thoughts. He kindly emailed me this response: Despite the fall in global CO2 emissions from 2008-2009 with the economic downturn and a 10% reduction in US emissions since 2005 (1), global emissions are roughly following the worst-case emission scenarios that will be used in the upcoming Intergovernmental Panel for Climate Change Report (2). Commentators are at odds about exactly what cuts the new policy will achieve, but if we optimistically assume that US emissions will follow the Copenhagen agreement and reduce by 17% from 2005-2020 (3), this could save up to 1000 million metric tonnes of global CO2 emissions (around 3% of current world values). If we further assume that this is a real global cut from the worse-case scenario and emissions growth elsewhere doesn’t compensate (as previously happened with huge growth in China over 2005-2011), we can go on to calculate the effect on atmospheric CO2 levels and temperature. To do this we estimated CO2 changes with the Bern pulse carbon cycle model (4) and temperature changes by using a simple model of climate (5) that is tuned to the latest climate model projections from our recent paper (6). These cuts acting alone would have a small but significant effect, reducing projected CO2 levels by 3 ppm in 2050 and 5 ppm in 2100, giving us between 0.02 and 0.04 C less warming in 2050 and staving off passing the 2C warming mark by 2-5 years. This may seem small as current levels of 400 ppm could easily pass 500 ppm by 2050, but every little helps. US emissions were 5940 million metric tonnes in 2005 and 5420 million metric tonnes in 2011. EDGAR database. http://edgar.jrc.ec.europa.eu/overview.php?v=CO2ts1990-2011&sort=des9  Scenario used is a “Representative Concentration Pathways\" (RCP) RCP8.5, see http://www.pik-potsdam.de/~mmalte/rcps/ http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/23/obama-is-announcing-new-climate-actions-tuesday-this-chart-explains-why/ http://unfccc.int/resource/brazil/carbon.html http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v6/n6/full/ngeo1836.html http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jgrd.50174/abstract","bodyHtml":"<p>Earlier, I noticed this tweet by <a href=\"http://www.see.leeds.ac.uk/people/p.forster\">Prof Piers Forster</a>, a climate scientist based at the University of Leeds...</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/piersforster/statuses/349681333267738624\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>I calculate Obama cuts until 2020 and then inaction leads to 1Gt CO2 saved each year and Earth 0.04 C cooler, crossing 2C 7 years later</p>&mdash; Piers Forster (@piersforster) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/piersforster/statuses/349681333267738624\">June 26, 2013</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <p>So I emailed him to ask if he could send me his more detailed thoughts. He kindly emailed me this response:</p> <blockquote> <p>Despite the fall in global CO2 emissions from 2008-2009 with the economic downturn and a 10% reduction in US emissions since 2005 (1), global emissions are roughly following the worst-case emission scenarios that will be used in the upcoming Intergovernmental Panel for Climate Change Report (2).</p> <p>Commentators are at odds about exactly what cuts the new policy will achieve, but if we optimistically assume that US emissions will follow the Copenhagen agreement and reduce by 17% from 2005-2020 (3), this could save up to 1000 million metric tonnes of global CO2 emissions (around 3% of current world values). If we further assume that this is a real global cut from the worse-case scenario and emissions growth elsewhere doesn’t compensate (as previously happened with huge growth in China over 2005-2011), we can go on to calculate the effect on atmospheric CO2 levels and temperature.</p> <p>To do this we estimated CO2 changes with the Bern pulse carbon cycle model (4) and temperature changes by using a simple model of climate (5) that is tuned to the latest climate model projections from our recent paper (6). These cuts acting alone would have a small but significant effect, reducing projected CO2 levels by 3 ppm in 2050 and 5 ppm in 2100, giving us between 0.02 and 0.04 C less warming in 2050 and staving off passing the 2C warming mark by 2-5 years. This may seem small as current levels of 400 ppm could easily pass 500 ppm by 2050, but every little helps.</p> <ol> <li>US emissions were 5940 million metric tonnes in 2005 and 5420 million metric tonnes in 2011. EDGAR database. <a href=\"http://edgar.jrc.ec.europa.eu/overview.php?v=CO2ts1990-2011&amp;sort=des9\">http://edgar.jrc.ec.europa.eu/overview.php?v=CO2ts1990-2011&amp;sort=des9</a> </li> <li>Scenario used is a “Representative Concentration Pathways&quot; (RCP) RCP8.5, see <a href=\"http://www.pik-potsdam.de/~mmalte/rcps/\">http://www.pik-potsdam.de/~mmalte/rcps/</a></li> <li><a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/23/obama-is-announcing-new-climate-actions-tuesday-this-chart-explains-why/\">http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/23/obama-is-announcing-new-climate-actions-tuesday-this-chart-explains-why/</a></li> <li><a href=\"http://unfccc.int/resource/brazil/carbon.html\">http://unfccc.int/resource/brazil/carbon.html</a></li> <li><a href=\"http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v6/n6/full/ngeo1836.html\">http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v6/n6/full/ngeo1836.html</a></li> <li><a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jgrd.50174/abstract\">http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jgrd.50174/abstract</a></li> </ol> </blockquote>","attributes":{},"id":"51cac596e4b023faee6c7c11","firstPublishedDate":"2013-06-26T10:42:55Z","publishedDate":"2013-06-26T10:42:55Z","contributors":[]},{"lastModifiedDate":"2013-06-26T10:31:18Z","lastModifiedBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"published":true,"createdDate":"2013-06-26T10:31:18Z","createdBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"elements":[{"assets":[],"textTypeData":{"html":"<p>Carbon Brief&apos;s Mat Hope delivers some <a href=\"http://www.carbonbrief.org/blog/2013/06/obama%E2%80%99s-all-of-the-above-climate-action-plan-sidesteps-congress-to-force-us-action\">sober analysis</a>:</p> \n<blockquote> \n <p>Obama&apos;s action plan will probably only have a <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2013/jun/25/obama-unveil-first-us-climate-strategy\"> limited impact</a> on the US&apos;s greenhouse gas emissions, but at least it will start to push the US towards serious climate action. The climate action plan is ultimately based on the hope that where Obama is heading, the rest of the government may follow.</p> \n</blockquote> \n<p>As does <a href=\"http://www.businessweek.com/ap/2013-06-26/whats-in-obamas-plan-to-combat-global-warming#p1\">Matthew Daly</a>, Associated Press&apos;s energy and environment correspondent:</p> \n<blockquote> \n <p>Legal challenges are a near certainty. Some legal experts question whether the Clean Air Act allows the EPA to limit carbon pollution from existing plants before finalizing rules for future plants. Roger Martella, an EPA general counsel under President George W. Bush, said Obama&apos;s proposals are &quot;very much in uncharted legal waters. This is not a settled area of law.&quot; Even if courts uphold the EPA&apos;s right to act, further legal challenges are likely. Scott Segal, director of the Electric Reliability Coordinating Council, a coalition of utilities and energy companies, said previous EPA regulations have had technical and methodological errors that had to be fixed, often under court order.</p> \n</blockquote>"},"type":"text"}],"bodyTextSummary":"Carbon Brief's Mat Hope delivers some sober analysis: Obama's action plan will probably only have a limited impact on the US's greenhouse gas emissions, but at least it will start to push the US towards serious climate action. The climate action plan is ultimately based on the hope that where Obama is heading, the rest of the government may follow. As does Matthew Daly, Associated Press's energy and environment correspondent: Legal challenges are a near certainty. Some legal experts question whether the Clean Air Act allows the EPA to limit carbon pollution from existing plants before finalizing rules for future plants. Roger Martella, an EPA general counsel under President George W. Bush, said Obama's proposals are \"very much in uncharted legal waters. This is not a settled area of law.\" Even if courts uphold the EPA's right to act, further legal challenges are likely. Scott Segal, director of the Electric Reliability Coordinating Council, a coalition of utilities and energy companies, said previous EPA regulations have had technical and methodological errors that had to be fixed, often under court order.","bodyHtml":"<p>Carbon Brief&apos;s Mat Hope delivers some <a href=\"http://www.carbonbrief.org/blog/2013/06/obama%E2%80%99s-all-of-the-above-climate-action-plan-sidesteps-congress-to-force-us-action\">sober analysis</a>:</p> <blockquote> <p>Obama&apos;s action plan will probably only have a <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2013/jun/25/obama-unveil-first-us-climate-strategy\"> limited impact</a> on the US&apos;s greenhouse gas emissions, but at least it will start to push the US towards serious climate action. The climate action plan is ultimately based on the hope that where Obama is heading, the rest of the government may follow.</p> </blockquote> <p>As does <a href=\"http://www.businessweek.com/ap/2013-06-26/whats-in-obamas-plan-to-combat-global-warming#p1\">Matthew Daly</a>, Associated Press&apos;s energy and environment correspondent:</p> <blockquote> <p>Legal challenges are a near certainty. Some legal experts question whether the Clean Air Act allows the EPA to limit carbon pollution from existing plants before finalizing rules for future plants. Roger Martella, an EPA general counsel under President George W. Bush, said Obama&apos;s proposals are &quot;very much in uncharted legal waters. This is not a settled area of law.&quot; Even if courts uphold the EPA&apos;s right to act, further legal challenges are likely. Scott Segal, director of the Electric Reliability Coordinating Council, a coalition of utilities and energy companies, said previous EPA regulations have had technical and methodological errors that had to be fixed, often under court order.</p> </blockquote>","attributes":{},"id":"51cac2f6e4b05e0c044bbb0d","firstPublishedDate":"2013-06-26T10:31:18Z","publishedDate":"2013-06-26T10:31:18Z","contributors":[]},{"lastModifiedDate":"2013-06-26T10:14:45Z","lastModifiedBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"published":true,"createdDate":"2013-06-26T10:14:03Z","createdBy":{"firstName":"Leo","lastName":"Hickman","email":"leo.hickman@guardian.co.uk"},"elements":[{"assets":[],"textTypeData":{"html":"<p>And here&apos;s some reaction from a range of environmental commentators and NGOs...</p> \n<blockquote> \n <p><strong><a href=\"http://insights.wri.org/news/2013/06/first-take-looking-president-obamas-climate-action-plan\">World Resources Institute</a></strong>: It will be important for the EPA to act with a sense of urgency in order to meet the U.S. emissions target. Just as important as the timeframe for finalizing these standards is their stringency. Without sufficient ambition, the United States will not be able to achieve the reductions it needs by 2020 and in the years beyond.</p> \n <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.biologicaldiversity.org/news/press_releases/2013/climate-plan-06-25-2013.html\"> Center for Biological Diversity</a></strong>: President Obama’s new climate plan takes modest steps toward reducing carbon pollution, but the strategy announced today will not cut emissions enough to prevent catastrophic warming and extreme weather dangers predicted by federal scientists. A key point in the president’s plan is a vague directive to the Environmental Protection Agency to establish carbon pollution standards for new and existing power plants — standards already required by law. The plan fails to address the Keystone XML pipeline, fracking on public lands and other dirty extreme-energy projects that could fatally undermine the climate change fight...The pollution control measures announced by the president today are aimed at fulfilling his administration’s pledge to put the United States on the path to cutting greenhouse gas emissions by 4 percent below 1990 levels by 2020. But such a reduction falls far short of what the U.S. pledged in the Kyoto Protocol and would not be enough to avert catastrophic temperature rises, according to climate scientists.</p> \n <p><strong>Bjorn Lomborg in </strong><a href=\"http://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2013/06/25/obama-climate-change-georgetown-column/2455723/\">USA Today</a>: Fracking is this decade&apos;s green solution. Obama recognizes gas as a &quot;bridge fuel.&quot; Replacing dirtier coal, cheaper gas from fracking has cut up to 500 MT of the U.S. CO2 emissions. This is 10 times more than what renewables do, and while renewables cost the U.S. tens of billions of dollars, fracking has saved the U.S. consumer $125 billion annually in cheaper energy prices. Fracking has local environmental issues, but these can all be addressed with good regulation. Moving the US fracking miracle to the rest of the world will be the biggest source of CO2 reductions this decade, and simultaneously increase global welfare by allowing energy access to billions yet unserved.</p> \n <p><strong>Nick Molho, head of climate and energy policy at WWF-UK</strong>: The president&apos;s plan wouldn’t reduce carbon pollution as much as scientists say is needed, but he rightly zeros in on executive branch actions, rather than waiting any longer for Congress. President Obama correctly sees this as an all-hands-on-deck moment requiring a government-wide plan, including action on pollution from the largest source of US emissions -- existing dirty power plants. Recognizing that the US needs to meet its international commitments and strongly support robust international action is also crucial as the world works to forge a new global climate pact by 2015.</p> \n <p><strong><a href=\"http://www.greenpeace.org/international/en/news/Blogs/makingwaves/obama-challenge-climate-energy-projects/blog/45723/\">Phil Radford</a>, executive director of Greenpeace USA</strong>: We proudly stand with Obama in the fight against carbon pollution, but we know that this fight won&apos;t be won with words alone...It&apos;s clear there&apos;s no room in our future for the Keystone pipeline, fracking, Arctic drilling, or giving away our public lands to the coal industry. Each of these projects will have a significant negative climate impact and not be in our national interest.</p> \n <p><strong><a href=\"http://content.sierraclub.org/press-releases/2013/06/sierra-club-statement-president-obama%E2%80%99s-climate-plan\">Michael Brune, executive director of the Sierra Club</a></strong>: The Sierra Club’s 2.1 million members and supporters issued a collective cheer as they heard the President declare that the most effective defense against climate disruption will be by tackling the biggest single source of carbon pollution: coal plants...While we must reduce pollution further to truly address dangerous climate disruption, we applaud the Administration’s continued commitment to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 17 percent by 2020. This plan includes key steps to reaching that goal, and we look forward to working with the Obama Administration to build on the progress laid out in today’s announcement.</p> \n</blockquote> \n<p>And here&apos;s a Google+ Hangout hosted by <a href=\"http://climatedesk.org/2013/06/live-blog-obama-rolls-out-climate-plan-2/\">ClimateDesk</a>&apos;s James West, featuring Grist&apos;s <a href=\"http://grist.org/author/david-roberts/\">David Roberts</a> and Mother Jones&apos;s <a href=\"http://www.motherjones.com/authors/kate-sheppard\">Kate Sheppar</a>d...</p>"},"type":"text"},{"assets":[{"file":"http://i1.ytimg.com/vi/s0nkzDJYyZg/hqdefault.jpg","mimeType":"image/jpeg","type":"image","typeData":{"width":480,"height":360}}],"type":"video","videoTypeData":{"width":460,"description":"Climate Desk: What You Should Know About Obama's Climate Plan","html":"<iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/s0nkzDJYyZg?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>","source":"YouTube","originalUrl":"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s0nkzDJYyZg","title":"Climate Desk: What You Should Know About Obama's Climate Plan","credit":"Climate Desk","url":"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s0nkzDJYyZg","height":259}}],"bodyTextSummary":"And here's some reaction from a range of environmental commentators and NGOs... World Resources Institute: It will be important for the EPA to act with a sense of urgency in order to meet the U.S. emissions target. Just as important as the timeframe for finalizing these standards is their stringency. Without suff